<TEXT>&#2;<DATELINE>2008-07-30</DATELINE><TITLE>Human Respiratory Viruses</TITLE><BODY>Viruses are the leading causes of acute lower respiratory-tract infection in infancy. Respiratory syncytial virus (RSV) is the most common pathogen, with hMPV, PIV-3, influenza viruses, and rhinoviruses accounting for the majority of the remainder of acute viral respiratory infections. Humans generally do not develop lifelong immunity to reinfection with these viruses; rather, specific immunity protects against severe and lower respiratory-tract disease.&#3;</BODY></TEXT>